Text: ' (February 12, 1809 – April 15, 1865) was the '
Reference: List of Presidents of the United States '16th President of the United States'
Text: ', serving from March 1861 until '
Reference: Assassination of Abraham Lincoln 'his assassination in April 1865'
Text: '. He successfully led his country through a great constitutional, military and moral crisis – the '
Reference: American Civil War ''
Text: ' – preserving the Union, while ending slavery, and promoting economic and financial modernization. Reared in a poor family on the western frontier, Lincoln was mostly self-educated. He became a country lawyer, a '
Reference: Whig Party (United States) 'Whig Party'
Text: ' '
Reference: Illinois House of Representatives 'Illinois state legislator'
Text: ', and a one-term member of the '
Reference: United States House of Representatives ''
Text: ', but failed in two attempts to be elected to the '
Reference: United States Senate ''
Text: ' as a '
Reference: History of the Republican Party (United States) 'new Republican Party'
Text: '.

After opposing the expansion of '
Reference: slavery in the United States ''
Text: ' in his campaign debates and speeches,<ref>Goodwin, p. 91; Holzer, p. 232.</ref> Lincoln secured the Republican nomination and was '
Reference: United States presidential election, 1860 'elected president in 1860'
Text: '. Before Lincoln took office in March, seven '
Reference: Southern United States 'southern slave states'
Text: ' declared their '
Reference: Secession in the United States 'secession'
Text: ' and formed the Confederacy. When war began with the Confederate attack on '
Reference: Fort Sumter ''
Text: ' on April 12, 1861, Lincoln concentrated on both the military and political dimensions of the war effort, seeking to reunify the nation. He vigorously exercised unprecedented war powers, including the arrest and detention without trial of thousands of suspected secessionists. He prevented British recognition of the '
Reference: Confederate States of America 'Confederacy'
Text: ' by skillfully handling the '
Reference: Trent Affair '''Trent'' affair'
Text: ' late in 1861.  His efforts toward the '
Reference: abolitionism 'abolition'
Text: ' of slavery include issuing his '
Reference: Emancipation Proclamation ''
Text: ' in 1863 and encouraging Congress to propose what would become the '
Reference: Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution 'Thirteenth Amendment'
Text: ' to the United States Constitution.

Lincoln closely supervised the war effort, especially the selection of top generals, including commanding general '
Reference: Ulysses S. Grant ''
Text: '. He brought leaders of various factions of his party into his cabinet and pressured them to cooperate. Under his leadership, the '
Reference: Union (American Civil War) 'Union'
Text: ' set up a naval blockade that shut down the South's normal trade, took control of the '
Reference: Border states (American Civil War) 'border slave states'
Text: ' at the start of the war, gained control of communications with gunboats on the southern river systems, and tried repeatedly to capture the Confederate capital at '
Reference: Richmond, Virginia 'Richmond'
Text: '. Each time a general failed, Lincoln substituted another until finally Grant succeeded in 1865. An exceptionally astute politician deeply involved with power issues in each state, he reached out to '
Reference: War Democrats ''
Text: ' and managed his own re-election in the '
Reference: United States presidential election, 1864 '1864 presidential election'
Text: '.

As the leader of the moderate faction of the Republican party, Lincoln found his policies and personality were "blasted from all sides": '
Reference: Radical Republicans ''
Text: ' demanded harsher treatment of the South, War Democrats desired more compromise, '
Reference: Copperheads (politics) 'Copperheads'
Text: ' despised him, and irreconcilable secessionists plotted his death.<ref>Tagg, p. xiii.</ref> Politically, Lincoln fought back with patronage, by pitting his opponents against each other, and by appealing to the American people with his powers of oratory.<ref>Randall (1947), pp. 65–87.</ref> His '
Reference: Gettysburg Address ''
Text: ' of 1863 became the most quoted speech in American history.<ref name'
Text: '"Bulla">Bulla (2010), p. 222.</ref> It was an iconic statement of America's dedication to the principles of nationalism, '
Reference: Republicanism in the United States 'republicanism'
Text: ', equal rights, liberty, and democracy. At the close of the war, Lincoln held a moderate view of '
Reference: Reconstruction Era of the United States 'Reconstruction'
Text: ', seeking to reunite the nation speedily through a policy of generous reconciliation in the face of lingering and bitter divisiveness. But six days after the surrender of Confederate commanding general '
Reference: Robert E. Lee ''
Text: ', Lincoln was '
Reference: Assassination of Abraham Lincoln 'assassinated'
Text: ' by Confederate sympathizer '
Reference: John Wilkes Booth ''
Text: '.  His death was the first assassination of a U.S. president and sent the nation  into '
Reference: Funeral and burial of Abraham Lincoln 'mourning'
Text: '. Lincoln has been consistently '
Reference: Historical rankings of Presidents of the United States#Scholar survey results 'ranked'
Text: ' by scholars and the public as one of the three greatest U.S. presidents.<ref name'
Text: '"Ranking Our Presidents">'
Link: http://history-world.org/pres.pdf '"Ranking Our Presidents"'
Text: '. James Lindgren. November 16, 2000. International World History Project.</ref><ref name'
Text: 'gallup>'
Link: http://www.gallup.com/poll/146183/Americans-Say-Reagan-Greatest-President.aspx '"Americans Say Reagan Is the Greatest President"'
Text: '. Gallup Inc. February 28, 2011.</ref>

'
Section [0] Family and childhood
Text: '
'
Section [1] Early life
Text: '
'
Begin Template: Main
k: Early life and career of Abraham Lincoln
End Template: Main
Text: '
Abraham Lincoln was born February 12, 1809, the second child of '
Reference: Thomas Lincoln ''
Text: ' and '
Reference: Nancy Lincoln ''
Text: ' (née Hanks), in a one-room log cabin on the '
Reference: Sinking Spring Farm ''
Text: ' in '
Reference: Hardin County, Kentucky 'Hardin County'
Text: ', Kentucky,<ref>Donald (1996), pp. 20–22.</ref> (now '
Reference: LaRue County, Kentucky 'LaRue County'
Text: ').  Lincoln's paternal grandfather and namesake, '
Reference: Abraham Lincoln (captain) 'Abraham'
Text: ', had moved his family from Virginia to '
Reference: Jefferson County, Kentucky 'Jefferson County'
Text: ', Kentucky,<ref name'
Text: '"Pessen2425">Pessen, pp. 24–25.</ref><ref name'
Text: '"white-12_13"/> where he was ambushed and killed in an Indian raid in 1786, with his children, including Lincoln's father Thomas, looking on.<ref name'
Text: '"white-12_13">White, pp. 12–13.</ref>  Thomas was left to make his own way on the frontier.<ref>Donald (1996), p. 21.</ref>  Lincoln's mother, Nancy, was the daughter of Lucy Hanks, and was born in what is now '
Reference: Mineral County, West Virginia 'Mineral County'
Text: ', West Virginia, then part of Virginia. Lucy moved with Nancy to Kentucky. Nancy Hanks married Thomas, who became a respected citizen. He bought and sold several farms, including the Sinking Spring Farm. The family attended a '
Reference: Separate Baptists ''
Text: ' church, which had high moral standards and opposed alcohol, dancing, and slavery.<ref>Donald (1996), pp. 22–24.</ref> Thomas enjoyed considerable status in Kentucky—where he sat on juries, appraised estates, served on country slave patrols, and guarded prisoners. By the time his son Abraham was born, Thomas owned two '
Begin Template: convert
k: 600
k: acre
k: ha
k: adj
Text: 'on'
End Template: convert
Text: ' farms, several town lots, livestock, and horses. He was among the richest men in the county.<ref name'
Text: '"Pessen2425"/><ref>Lamb, p. 189.</ref> However, in 1816, Thomas lost all of his land in court cases because of faulty '
Reference: title (property) 'property titles'
Text: '.<ref name'
Text: '"sandberg-20"/>

'
Reference: File:Young Lincoln By Charles Keck.JPG 'thumb|left|The young Lincoln in sculpture at Senn Park, Chicago|alt=A statue of young Lincoln sitting on a stump, holding a book open on his lap'
Text: '

The family moved north across the Ohio River to free (i.e., non-slave) territory and made a new start in '
Reference: Perry County, Indiana 'Perry County'
Text: ', Indiana.  Lincoln later noted that this move was "partly on account of slavery" but mainly due to land title difficulties.<ref name'
Text: '"sandberg-20">Sandburg (1926), p. 20.</ref> In Indiana, when Lincoln was nine, his mother Nancy died of '
Reference: milk sickness ''
Text: ' in 1818.<ref name'
Text: '"donald-1996-p30-33"/>  After the death of Lincoln's mother, his older sister, '
Reference: Sarah Lincoln Grigsby 'Sarah'
Text: ', took charge of caring for him until their father remarried in 1819; Sarah later died in her 20s while giving birth to a stillborn son.<ref>Donald (1996), p. 20.</ref>

Thomas Lincoln's new wife was the widow '
Reference: Sarah Bush Lincoln 'Sarah Bush Johnston'
Text: ', the mother of three of her own children. Lincoln became very close to his stepmother, and referred to her as "Mother".<ref>Donald (1996), pp. 26–27.</ref>  As a pre-teen, he did not like the hard labor associated with frontier life. Some in his family, and in the neighborhood, for a time considered him to be lazy.<ref>White, pp. 25, 31, 47.</ref><ref>Donald (1996), p. 33.</ref> As he grew into his teens, he willingly took responsibility for all chores expected of him as one of the boys in the household and became an adept axeman in his work building rail fences. He attained a reputation for brawn and audacity after a very competitive wrestling match to which he was challenged by the renowned leader of a group of ruffians, "the Clary's Grove boys".<ref>Donald (1996), p. 41.</ref>  Lincoln also agreed with the customary obligation of a son to give his father all earnings from work done outside the home until age 21.<ref name'
Text: '"donald-1996-p30-33">Donald (1996), pp. 30–33.</ref> In later years, Lincoln occasionally loaned his father money.<ref>Donald (1996), pp. 28, 152.</ref> Lincoln became increasingly distant from his father, in part because of his father's lack of education.  While young Lincoln's formal elementary education consisted approximately of a year's worth of classes from several itinerant teachers, he was mostly self-educated and was an avid reader.<ref>Donald (1996), pp. 38–43; Prokopowicz, pp. 18–19.</ref>

In 1830, fearing a milk sickness outbreak along the Ohio River, the Lincoln family moved west, where they settled on public land in '
Reference: Macon County, Illinois 'Macon County'
Text: ', Illinois, another free, non-slave state.<ref>Donald (1996), p. 36.</ref> In 1831, Thomas relocated the family to a '
Reference: Lincoln Log Cabin State Historic Site 'new homestead'
Text: ' in '
Reference: Coles County, Illinois 'Coles County'
Text: ', Illinois. It was then that, as an ambitious 22-year-old, Lincoln decided to seek a better life and struck out on his own.  Canoeing down the '
Reference: Sangamon River ''
Text: ', Lincoln ended up in the village of '
Reference: New Salem, Menard County, Illinois 'New Salem'
Text: ' in '
Reference: Sangamon County, Illinois 'Sangamon County'
Text: '.<ref>Thomas (2008), pp. 23–53; Carwardine (2003), pp. 3–5.</ref> In the spring of 1831, hired by New Salem businessman '
Reference: Denton Offutt ''
Text: ' and accompanied by friends, he took goods by '
Reference: flatboat ''
Text: ' from New Salem to New Orleans via the Sangamon, Illinois, and Mississippi rivers. After arriving in New Orleans—and witnessing slavery firsthand—he walked back home.<ref>Sandburg (1926), pp. 22–23.</ref>

'
