Text: '

In 1832, at age 23, Lincoln and a partner bought a small general store on credit in '
Reference: Lincoln's New Salem 'New Salem'
Text: ', Illinois. Although the economy was booming in the region, the business struggled and Lincoln eventually sold his share. That March he began his political career with his first campaign for the '
Reference: Illinois General Assembly ''
Text: '. He had attained local popularity and could draw crowds as a natural raconteur in New Salem, though he lacked an education, powerful friends, and money, which may be why he lost. He advocated navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.<ref>Winkle ch 7–8.'
Begin Template: page needed
