As the war drew to a close, Lincoln's presidential Reconstruction for the South was in flux; having believed the federal government had limited responsibility to the millions of '
Reference: freedmen ''
Text: '.  He signed into law Senator Charles Sumner's '
Reference: Freedman's Bureau ''
Text: ' bill that set up a temporary federal agency designed to meet the immediate material needs of former slaves. The law assigned land for a lease of three years with the ability to purchase title for the freedmen.  Lincoln stated that his Louisiana plan did not apply to all states under Reconstruction. Shortly before his assassination, Lincoln announced he had a new plan for southern Reconstruction.  Discussions with his cabinet revealed Lincoln planned short-term military control over southern states, until readmission under the control of southern Unionists.<ref>Carwardine (2003), pp. 242–243.</ref>

'
Section [1] Redefining the republic and republicanism
Text: '
'
Reference: File:Lincoln-Warren-1865-03-06.jpeg 'thumb|upright|left|alt=An older tired looking Lincoln with a beard.|The last high-quality photograph of Lincoln was taken March 1865.'
Text: '

The successful reunification of the states had consequences for the name of the country. The term "the United States" has historically been used, sometimes in the plural ("these United States"), and other times in the singular, without any particular grammatical consistency. The Civil War was a significant force in the eventual dominance of the singular usage by the end of the 19th century.<ref name'
Text: '"Presidential Proclamation">'
